			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2019</a> paper:</span><br><i>A vision of miking: interactive programmatic modeling, sound language composition, and self-learning compilation</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DavidBroman.html">David Broman</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3357766.3359531">10.1145/3357766.3359531</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The paper mainly targets domain-specific languages or modeling languages, including their design or use.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It includes substantial tool support or infrastructure relevant for engineering/using languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It relies on formal methods (definitions/proofs/semantic properties) beyond informal description.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes modularity/composition/integration (embedding or coordinating language components).
</li></ul></li></ul>
